2.3.1 Exercises

  1. Relationship between cty and hwy.
mpg %>% ggplot(aes(cty, hwy)) +
  geom_point()

  • Relationship is linear, positive, and strong without any glaring outliers. The only concern I have about the plot is that it is almost too perfect. Perhaps multicollinearity?
  • The problem is there are too many x-axis labels, so its impossible to read the values. One fix would be to shorten the model names: get rid of drv values ,manufacturers, and spaces. If this does not suffice, rotate the x-axis values 90 degrees.
  1. The first two graphs will be scatterplots. #1 graph will have a high correlation and be linear, as we saw above. #2 graph should show a positive relationship (common sense?). #3 graph will be a line graph that changes with time (x-axis). #4 graph will be a histogram with counts of cty on the y-axis.

2.4.1 Exercises

  • Based upon these graphs, mapping color to categorical variable is informative while mapping it to continiuous variable is not.

Error: A continuous variable can not be mapped to shape

Mapping categorical variable to shape works (produces a graph), but readability is very poor. Mapping to continuous variable throws an error

# Mapping to categoorical variable
ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) +
  geom_point(aes(size = drv))
Warning: Using size for a discrete variable is not advised.

# Mapping to continuous variable
ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) +
  geom_point(aes(size = year))

* Mapping categorical/continuous variable to size works, but readbility is very poor.

Using 2 aesthetics in a plot

Warning: Using size for a discrete variable is not advised.

* Ah, readability is much better.

  1. When you map a continuous variable to shape, you get an error. Why:The shape palette can deal with a maximum of 6 discrete values because more than 6 becomes difficult to discriminate (ggplot2 documentation).
Warning: The shape palette can deal with a maximum of 6 discrete values
because more than 6 becomes difficult to discriminate; you have
10. Consider specifying shapes manually if you must have them.
Warning: Removed 96 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

* ggplot2 only takes 6 discrete values! If we want more shapes, we have to manually designate them.

library(tidyverse)
ggplot(mpg, aes(cty, displ)) +
  geom_point() +

* When faceting by a continuous variable hwy, I get alot of graphs here with little information in each graph. I don’t imagine these graphs to be useful.

ggplot(mpg, aes(cty, displ)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~cyl)

* You see some information for all the cylinders except 5 cylinder graph.

  • I think the key difference is that a continous variable has so many values that its impossible to get alot of information for each facetted graph. It has minimal information. On the other hand, for categorical variables, there are not many facetted graphs, so you get a reasonable amount of information from each graph.
ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, cty)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~cyl)

* First, you can’t really say much about 5 cylinder cars since there are only two data points for them. for 4 cylinder cars, most cars have small engine displacement and high fuel economy (compared to 6 and 8 cylinder cars). For 6 cylinder cars, the engine displacement ranges from 3 to 4 liters, but has low fuel economy. Last, for 8 cylinder cars, it is on the high range of engine displacement, but has low fuel economy.

3.2.1 Exercises

  • Scatterplot: geom_point()
  • Line Chart: geom_line()
  • Histogram: geom_histogram()
  • Bar chart: geom_bar()
  • Pie chart: According to http://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/reference/coord_polar.html , the polar coordinate system is most commonly used for pie charts, which are a stacked bar chart in polar coordinates. A pie chart = stacked bar chart + polar coordinates (geom_bar() + coord_polar())

  1. Polygons are very similar to paths (as drawn by geom_path) except that the start and end points are connected and the inside is coloured by fill. The group aesthetic determines which cases are connected together into a polygon. geom_path() connects the observations in the order in which they appear in the data. geom_line() connects them in order of the variable on the x axis.

  2. Not sure what Hadley means by low-level geoms Here is some information on parameters used in geom_smooth(). http://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/reference/geom_smooth.html geom_boxplot(): http://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/reference/geom_boxplot.html geom_violin(): http://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/reference/geom_violin.html

library(tidyverse)
ggplot(economics, aes(date, unemploy)) +
  geom_line()

presidential <- subset(presidential, start > economics$date[1])
ggplot(economics) +
  geom_rect(
    aes(xmin = start, xmax = end, fill = party),
    ymin = -Inf, ymax = Inf, alpha = 0.2,
    data = presidential
  ) +
  geom_vline(
    aes(xintercept = as.numeric(start)),
    data = presidential,
    colour = "grey50", alpha = 0.5
  ) +
  geom_text(
    aes(x = start, y = 2500, label = name),
    data = presidential,
    size = 3, vjust = 0, hjust = 0, nudge_x = 50
  ) +
  geom_line(aes(date, unemploy)) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("blue", "red"))

mod <- loess(hwy ~ displ, data = mpg) 
smoothed <- data.frame(displ = seq(1.6, 7, length = 50))
pred <- predict(mod, newdata = smoothed, se = TRUE) 
smoothed$hwy <- pred$fit 
smoothed$hwy_lwr <- pred$fit - 1.96 * pred$se.fit # code to find lower range 
smoothed$hwy_upr <- pred$fit + 1.96 * pred$se.fit # code to find upper range 

# We should extract from smoothed the outlier points (outside the lower and upper ranges)
outlier <- filter(smoothed, hwy < hwy_lwr | hwy > hwy_upr)

5.7.1 Exericses

?position_nudge()
  • position_nudge is generally useful for adjusting the position of items on discrete scales by a small amount. Nudging is built in to geom_text because it’s so useful for moving labels a small distance from what they’re labelling.

  1. Need Help here

  2. Borrowed from U of Chicago Rather than adding random noise, geom_count() counts the number of observations at each location, then maps the count to point area. The more observations are located at that area, the larger the point.

  3. Borrowed from this Source With a stacked area plot, it is hard to interpret the magnitude of the area of each color because of the colors below it. With the line plot, you can interpret the trends for each region and area for each region easier. An advantage of a stacked area plot is its differentiability. With colored areas you can easily distinguish between areas underneath the line and thus, distinguish the trends.
